title: For Sale/Trade:  1997 Plymouth Grand Voyager (aka the Beast)
postcontent:
So...it's called the beast for 2 reasons. First, we've basically tried to kill this car. It has 234xxx miles on it but it still runs strong. The engine just keeps on going. Second, because it roars to life.

Here's the deal - this was our daily driver for a family of five until late last year. Last year we replaced the battery, all of the tires, put in a new alternator, put in a new (used) transmission, put on a new break line, etc. The year before we put in different breaks and new spark plugs and new wires. I didn't realize that we already had more spark plugs just sitting under the dash, so we have another 6 spark plugs and another light that are currently just sitting there under the radio - consider them a gift if you buy this car. So - that's all good & well, but then a few months ago we broke the windshield wiper & I'm just DONE. I don't want to fix it anymore. When you turn on the windshields, they sort of do a little dance & slap each other. It's kind of funny, and to fix it would probably cost like $50 for the part, but I don't care. We bought a different van & have been sporadically driving this van around ever since. Now I'm tired of looking at it, and thought I'd try to sell it on Craigslist before taking it to a yard.

The van is what it is - it's old and beat up, but runs great. It has power windows that work. The AC worked last time I drove it. It does have an oil leak - it leaks about a quart every 1000 miles. So, I just check the oil & dump in a new quart a few times between oil changes.

There are obvious rust spots, that we will show you on pictures if you want this van after I wrote all of this. Oh - and it roars to life (quite literally) because the muffler has a split down the seam...aka it's pretty loud.

So, that's pretty much the most honest thing I can write about this car. It's for sale or trade - would be a decent car for a family that doesn't have much money & maybe can fix the windshield wiper...

title: For Sale:  WTS/WTT: Yugoslavian Zastava M48 Mauser  7.92x57mm (8mm Mauser)
postcontent:
Up for sale is a fine example of a Yugoslavian Zastava M48 Mauser in 7.92x57mm (8mm Mauser). This rifle is in excellent condition, with all matching numbers. Blueing is about 98% with very little wear on moving part surfaces. Excellent bore, shiny with strong rifling. The wood has a minor scratches and dents from handling but nothing that really attracts attention. It appears this one was never issued (Most of the M48s that were made were put into storage soon after manufacture because the Yugos were fielding their variant of the semiautomatic SKS at about the same time). It has one of the nicest two stage triggers that I have encountered on a military Mauser. Has standard ramp sights, with a hooded front sight. The barrel is 23.25" long.

Yugoslavia produced the M48 with FN tooling from 1950 to the early 1960's. They are similar to the previous issue Yugo 24/47 but received a couple of minor upgrades that were inspired by the German K98k (of which the Yugos captured many and also refurbished). Like the K98k, the M48 features a turned-down bolt which makes it easier to manipulate from certain positions and gave the rifle a slimmer, refined feel. Also similar to the 98K is a stock with sling cutouts instead of sling swivels. The M48 will accept the K98k sling and bayonet and uses standard stripper clips to load quickly.

8mm Mauser ammunition is one of the only calibers you can still find "cheap" surplus ammo available making it more economical to shoot than the more in demand calibers like .308 and .223 right now. While it's not nearly as cheap as it was a few years ago, you can still find it for under $0.30 per round. The 8mm does everything the .30-06 will do and loaded to their full potential, many will argue the 8mm does it better. I've almost talked myself out of selling the rifle but I have financial obligations that require me to sell.

Asking $350 OBO. Can meet for a FTF deal in Lincoln county, or ship at your expense. I can ship to your door if you're in Nebraska (yes, this is completely legal under state and federal law) but I will need a copy an 01 or 03 FFL to ship to if out of state. Trade interests include ammunition (5.56mm, 7.62x39mm, .308, 6.8SPC, 9mm, 45acp), a .357 magnum revolver or lever action, or other pistols/rifles. Let me know what you got, the worst I'll do is politely decline. Additional pictures available via email upon request.

title: For Sale/Trade:  NIB Les Baer UTC 1911
postcontent:
Selling my NIB Les Baer Ultimate Tactical Carry model. I purchased this gun new from Kames in Canton a year ago and it has been sitting unfired in my safe since then. I'm selling it to fund a different Baer model.

As I said, this is the 5 inch Ultimate Tactical Carry model. It has the fixed night sights, single sided safety and the thin Cocobolo grips. The sharp edges have also been nicely blended which I find to be both functional and good looking. This gun also has the blued finish. Les Baer builds an incredible 1911, but their blue finish seems to be hit or miss at times. I can honestly say that the finish on this gun is perfect. I see a lot of Baers with different shades of finish on the frame and slide when they are new, but the bluing on this gun matches perfectly. No scrapes or scratches anywhere, as you would expect from a new gun.

The frame to slide fit is perfect, and the lockup is tight as a drum. Anyone familiar with Les Baer 1911s knows how tight some of them can be, and this one is no exception. As with most of the semi-custom manufacturers, Baer recommends a 500 round break-in period for each of their guns, after which they smooth out considerably. Whoever buys this 1911 will have the pleasure of getting to know the gun during the break-in, as you will be the first to fire it outside of the factory.

I have many close-up high resolution pictures uploaded to my Photobucket page. Unfortunately, Armslist does not allow clickable links in their ads, and some people have still not figured out how to copy and paste, so send me an email and I will answer any questions you have as well as send you the link to the pictures. It's very rare to find a high-end 1911 on Armslist that is not for sale by a dealer, so get it while you can and skip the taxes. Buyer must be over 21 years old, have a valid Ohio drivers license and be able to legally own a firearm in the state of Ohio. CCW holders are preferred but not required. If more than one person responds to the ad, I will give priority to anyone with a CCW. Thanks for looking.

The next-generation PMAG 30 GEN M3 is a 30-round 5.56x45 NATO (.223 Remington) polymer magazine for AR15/M4 compatible weapons. Along with expanded feature set and compatibility, the GEN M3 incorporates new material technology and manufacturing processes for enhanced strength, durability, and reliability to exceed rigorous military performance specifications.

Modified internal and external geometry also permits operation with a wide range of non Colt-spec platforms such as the HK® 416 and MR556A1, M27 IAR, British SA-80, FN® SCAR™ MK 16/16S, and others. A redesigned bolt catch notch in the rear of the magazine provides increased bolt catch clearance, while an over-travel stop on the spine helps ensure the magazine will not over-insert on compatible weapons.

Similar to the MOE PMAG, the GEN M3 features a long-life stainless steel spring, four-way anti-tilt follower and constant-curve internal geometry for reliable feeding, and simple tool-less disassembly to ease cleaning. In addition, an included pop-off Impact/Dust Cover can optionally be used to minimize debris intrusion and protect against potential damage during storage and transit. Low profile ribs and new aggressive front and rear texture gives positive control of the GEN M3 in all environments, and a paint pen dot matrix has been added to the bottom panel of the body to allow easy marking by the end user for identification. The new, easy to disassemble flared floorplate aids extraction and handling of the magazine while providing improved drop protection, but is slightly slimmer than before for better compatibility with tight double and triple magazine pouches.
Made in U.S.A.
